<p>title: Integrated Test<br />
subtitle: MultiMarkdown test suite<br />
author: Fletcher T. Penney</p>

<p>This file is a designed as a single test that incorporates most of
the <em>commonly</em> used MultiMarkdown features. This allows a single test file to
identify common structures that are not supported yet -- particularly useful
when developing a new output format.</p>

<h1>Core Markdown Features</h1>

<h2>Basic Block Level Elements</h2>

<h3>Paragraphs</h3>

<p>Normal paragraphs consist of plain text.</p>

<p>They are separated by empty lines.</p>

<p>Long lines of text will wrap naturally as needed to ensure that they fit in the available space. This will vary by format, of course.</p>

<p>By including two spaces at the end of a line<br />
a linebreak is inserted.</p>

<p>MultiMarkdown adds the ability to use<br />
an &quot;escaped newline&quot; for this as well.</p>

<h3>Headers</h3>

<p>ATX headers and Setext headers are used in this document</p>

<pre><code>## ATX Header 2 ##

Setext Header 1
===============

Setext Header 2
---------------
</code></pre>

<h3>Blockquotes</h3>

<p>This is a normal paragraph.</p>

<blockquote>
<p>This is a blockquote.</p>

<p>With two paragraphs.</p>

<blockquote>
<p>And a nested blockquote.
(Which doesn't work well in Beamer.)</p>
</blockquote>
</blockquote>

<h3>Unordered Lists</h3>

<p>Lists can be &quot;tight&quot; or &quot;loose&quot;.</p>

<p>Unordered/tight:</p>

<ul>
<li>foo</li>
<li>bar</li>
<li>bat</li>
</ul>

<p>Unordered/loose:</p>

<ul>
<li><p>foo</p></li>
<li><p>bar</p></li>
<li><p>bat</p></li>
</ul>

<h3>Ordered Lists</h3>

<p>Lists can be &quot;tight&quot; or &quot;loose&quot;.</p>

<p>Ordered/tight:</p>

<ol>
<li>foo</li>
<li>bar</li>
<li>bat</li>
</ol>

<p>Ordered/loose:</p>

<ol>
<li><p>foo</p></li>
<li><p>bar</p></li>
<li><p>bat</p></li>
</ol>

<h3>Complex Lists</h3>

<p>Lists can contain other elements</p>

<ul>
<li><p>A list item.</p>

<p>With a second paragraph.</p></li>
<li><p>An item.</p>

<ol>
<li>With</li>
<li>a</li>
<li>sublist</li>
</ol></li>
</ul>

<h3>Code Blocks</h3>

<p>Code blocks are indented with 4 spaces or 1 tab.</p>

<pre><code>This is a code block.

As is this.
</code></pre>

<h3>Horizontal Rules</h3>

<p>You can include horizontal rules</p>

<hr />

<p>between paragraphs and other elements.</p>

<h3>HTML Blocks</h3>

<p>HTML blocks can be included, but will work differently when not exporting to HTML, of course.</p>

<div>*foo*</div>

<div>

<p><em>bar</em></p>

</div>

<h2>Basic Span Level Elements</h2>

<h3>Links</h3>

<p>Links can be <a href="http://example.com/inline" title="Inline Link">inline</a>, or <a href="http://example.com/reference" title="Reference Link">reference</a>.</p>

<p>You can also use automatic links <a href="http://example.com/auto">http://example.com/auto</a>
and email <a href="mailto:auto@example.com">auto@example.com</a>.</p>

<h3>Emphasis</h3>

<p>Text can be <em>emphasized</em>, <strong>strong</strong>, or <strong><em>both</em></strong>.</p>

<h3>Code</h3>

<p>You can include <code>code()</code> in the middle of other text.</p>

<h3>Images</h3>

<p>Images are similar to links, but with a leading <code>!</code>.</p>

<p><img src="test-image.png" alt="image" title="Image title" />\ </p>

<h3>Backslash Escapes</h3>

<p>*This is not emphasized.*</p>

<p>[This is not a link][].</p>

<p>* This is not a list item</p>

<h3>Inline HTML</h3>

<p>HTML can be included within other blocks.</p>

<p>(Markdown does not parse markup inside these HTML spans, whereas MultiMarkdown tries to.)</p>

<p>This is text with <foo><em>bar</em></foo> HTML.</p>

<h1>MultiMarkdown Features</h1>

<h2>Extended Block Level Elements</h2>

<h3>Metadata</h3>

<p>Metadata can be included at the top of a document.</p>

<pre><code>Title:		Integrated Test  
Subtitle:	MultiMarkdown test suite  
Author:		Fletcher T. Penney  
</code></pre>

<p>It can be referenced with <code>[%title]</code> to insert the meta value - [%title].</p>

<h3>Header Cross-References</h3>

<p>MultiMarkdown automatically generates anchors for headers, to allow for navigation,
such as jumping back to the previous [Metadata][] section.</p>

<h3>Table of Contents</h3>

<p>MultiMarkdown can generate a TOC from the header structure.</p>

<p>{{TOC}}</p>

<h3>Fenced Code Blocks</h3>

<p><code>Fenced code blocks are easier in some circumstances.</code></p>

<h3>Definition Lists</h3>

<p>Term 1
Term 2
: Definition 1
: Definition 2</p>

<h3>Tables</h3>

<p>| foo | bar |<br />
-----+ | :--:+ |<br />
| <em>foo</em> | <em>bar</em> |<br />
| <strong>foo bar</strong> ||</p>

<h3>Figures</h3>

<p>An image in a paragraph by itself becomes a figure.</p>

<p>![image2]</p>

<h2>Extended Span Level Elements</h2>

<h3>Footnotes</h3>

<p>Foo.[^This is an inline footnote]</p>

<p>Bar.[^foot]</p>

<p>[^foot]: And a reference footnote.</p>

<h3>Citations</h3>

<p>An inline citation.[#Inline Citation]</p>

<p>A reference citation.<a href="bar">#foo</a></p>

<h3>Glossaries</h3>

<p>[?term]</p>

<p>[?term]: A term to be defined.</p>

<h3>Abbreviations</h3>

<p><a href="MultiMarkdown">&gt;MMD</a> and <a href="MultiMarkdown">&gt;MMD</a>.</p>

<h3>Image attributes</h3>

<p>Images can have attributes.</p>

<p>![image2]\ </p>

<p>[image2]: test-image.png &quot;Image title&quot; width=40px</p>

<h3>Math</h3>

<p>foo \\({e}^{i\pi }+1=0\\) bar</p>

<p>\\[ {x}_{1,2}=\frac{-b\pm \sqrt{{b}^{2}-4ac}}{2a} \\]</p>

<p>foo ${e}^{i\pi }+1=0$ bar</p>

<p>foo ${e}^{i\pi }+1=0$, bar</p>

<p>$${x}_{1,2}=\frac{-b\pm \sqrt{{b}^{2}-4ac}}{2a}$$</p>

<h3>Smart Quotes</h3>

<p>&quot;foo&quot; and 'bar' -- with --- dashes...</p>

<h3>CriticMarkup</h3>

<p>{++Insert++}</p>

<p>{--Delete--}</p>

<p>{~~Old~&gt;New~~}</p>

<p>{&gt;&gt;Comment&lt;&lt;}</p>

<p>{==Highlighted==}</p>
